This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.

Summary:
1. Primary Request and Intent:
   The user asked me to "Read prompt.md and complete the exercise following the workflow rules." The exercise is the MHPCO Claim Office Kata — a TypeScript implementation of an insurance system for magical items with two operations (quote and claim). The workflow follows strict TDD with skills: test-list (create it.todo list), red (activate one test with predictions), green (minimal implementation), and refactor (agent-based). One test at a time, with explicit Correct/Incorrect prediction blocks per cycle (parsed mechanically for metrics).

2. Key Technical Concepts:
   - TDD red-green-refactor cycle with skill-based phase transitions
   - TypeScript with strict typing, ES modules (.js imports)
   - Vitest test framework, pnpm package manager
   - Insurance domain: base premiums, per-item surcharges (cursed +50%, high enchantment ≥5 +30%), policy discounts (loyalty ≥2yrs -20%, follow-up -15%), per-item first insurance +10%, processing fee 5G
   - Component blocks: 3 alike components → 60G special premium
   - Claim processing: 100G deductible per damage, 2x insurance cap, enchantment ≥8 50% reimbursement, dragon material full reimbursement
   - Rounding in MHPCO's favor (premium up via Math.ceil, payout down via Math.floor)
   - APP (Atomic Properties of Programs) mass calculation for refactoring decisions
   - Functional patterns: reduce, map, filter, predicate arrays

3. Files and Code Sections:
   - `/prompt.md` — kata specification (already read in full earlier)

   - `/src/claim-office.spec.ts` — test file with 38 tests; 26 currently passing, 12 todo
